         <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" source="#jmr2007">
            <p>a. [? The sarcophagus belongs to male name and to female name] his wife, and their children, the Aurelii Artemidoros and Zosimos. No one else may be buried in the sarcophagus and if anyone buries anyone apart from those named he shall pay to the most eminent council of the People of Mastaura three thousand denarii. The copy of this inscription is filed in the [?city's archive - - -</p>
            <p>b. They are still living.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Since formulae as well as lettering are a little different from those of Aphrodisias, the text was clearly drafted and cut at Mastaura (in the foothills on the north side of the Maeander Valley, between Nysa and Antioch on the Maeander). The owning family had probably received Roman citizenship under the Edict of Caracalla in A.D. 212. Although their funerary fine is not a high one, they may have been a family of some local consequence since their tomb was under the protection of the city council.</p>
         </div>
